ue their interests and define themselves. Although both governments regard the border as clearly defined, local communities continue to contest the artificial divisions imposed by the international boundary and define spatial and human relationships in the borderlands in their own terms. The debate is often cast in terms of Canada’s failure to recognize the 1794 Jay Treaty’s confirmation of Native rights to transport goods into Canada, but ultimately the issue concerns the larger struggle of First Nations to force recognition of their people’s rights to move freely across the border in search of economic and social independence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistory. 0aIndians of North AmericazGreat Lakes Region (North America)xHistoryvCongresses. 0aIndians of North AmericazGreat Lakes Region (North America)xHistory. 0aM©♭tiszGreat Lakes Region (North America)xHistoryvCongresses. 0aM©♭tiszGreat Lakes Region (North America)xHistory. 0aRacially mixed peoplezGreat Lakes Region (North America)xHistoryvCongresses. 0aRacially mixed peoplezGreat Lakes Region (North America)xHistory. 0aWater boundarieszOntario. 0aWater boundarieszUnited States. 4aIndigenous Studies. 4aPolitical Science. 4aPolitical Science: International Relations. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh1 aBellfy, Phil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChute, Janet E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanzinger, Edmund J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFehr, Rick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Michelle A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHele, Karl S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHele, Karl 